problem:
For how many positive integral values of $a$ is it true that $x = 2$ is the only positive integer solution of the system of inequalities $$
\begin{cases}
2x>3x-3\\
3x-a>-6
\end{cases}
$$

For how many positive integral values of $a$ is it true that $x = 2$ is the only positive integer solution of the system of inequalities $$
\begin{cases}
2x>3x-3\\
3x-a>-6
\end{cases}
$$

response:
Let's solve the system of inequalities first. The first inequality is $2x > 3x - 3$, which simplifies to $0 > x - 3$, i.e., $x < 3$. Therefore, the only positive integer solution for $x$ is $x = 1$ or $x = 2$.<then>\begin{align*}
\text{Let's start by solving the second inequality.} & \end{align*}<then>\begin{align*}
3x - a > -6 & \implies 3x + 6 > a & \implies a < 3x + 6 \\
\text{If } x = 1, & \text{ then } a < 9 \\
\text{If } x = 2, & \text{ then } a < 12 \\
\end{align*}<then>\begin{align*}
\text{So, we need to find the positive integer values of } a \text{ that satisfy both } a < 9 \text{ and } a < 12. \\
\text{Since } x = 2 \text{ is the only positive integer solution, } a \text{ must be less than the upper bound of the smallest solution's } x \text{ value, i.e., } a < 9. \\
\text{Therefore, } a \text{ can take the values } 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, \text{ or } 8. \\
\text{So, the number of positive integral values of } a \text{ is } \boxed{9}. & \end{align*}

### Answer:

The number of positive integral values of $a$ for which $x = 2$ is the only positive integer solution of the system of inequalities is \(\boxed{9}\).

